<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="586" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,967,2038]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1111,1138]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Externally 
<taxonomicName authority="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan, 2020" authorityName="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan" authorityYear="2020" box="[450,543,1112,1138]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gesar" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[450,543,1112,1138]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. gesar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[549,638,1112,1138]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[549,638,1112,1138]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Huang" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Huang" authorityYear="2020" box="[781,1122,1112,1138]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shingwa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[781,904,1112,1138]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. shingwa</emphasis>
Volynkin &amp; Huang
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1128,1217,1112,1138]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1128,1217,1112,1138]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in sharing a similar contrasting color pattern on forewing, but 
<taxonomicName authority="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan, 2020" authorityName="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan" authorityYear="2020" box="[626,719,1148,1174]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gesar" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[626,719,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. gesar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[727,816,1148,1174]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[727,816,1148,1174]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be immediately distinguished from the latter by its male genital segments of abdomen covered with blackish scales, broader reddish pattern elements and hindwing mostly pinkish, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Huang" authorityYear="2020" box="[460,584,1220,1246]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shingwa">
<emphasis box="[460,584,1220,1246]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. shingwa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the male genital segments of abdomen are covered with pale yellow scales, reddish pattern elements are significantly narrower and hindwing is mostly yellowish, only slightly tinted with pink in the submarginal zone as well as the totally different aedeagus vesica structure. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan, 2020" authorityName="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan" authorityYear="2020" box="[1303,1396,1292,1318]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gesar" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1303,1396,1292,1318]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. gesar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="4" pageNumber="586" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin, 2018" authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2018" box="[531,798,1328,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garo">
<emphasis box="[531,616,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. garo</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Volynkin, A. V." box="[624,798,1328,1354]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref5559" refString="Volynkin, A. V. (2018) Four new species of the genus Barsine Walker, 1854 (Lepidoptera: Erebidae, Arctiinae) from Oriental Region. Far Eastern Entomologist, 358, 1 - 18 https: // doi. org / 10.25221 / fee. 358.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Volynkin, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[814,944,1328,1354]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1865,1890]" captionTargetBox="[241,1348,192,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[230,1358,181,1839]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 7–14. Ammatho (Ammathella) spp. adults. 7, A. gesar sp. nov., holotype male, SW China, Xizang (SCAU); 8, A. gesar sp. nov., paratype male, SW China, Xizang (SCAU); 9, A. shingwa sp. nov., holotype male, NE Myanmar, Kachin (MWM/ZSM); 10, A. shingwa sp. nov., paratype female, NE Myanmar, Kachin (MWM/ZSM); 11, A. garo, holotype male, NE India, Assam (MWM/ZSM); 12, A. garo, paratype male, NE India, Assam (MWM/ZSM); 13, A. midzhan, holotype male, NE Myanmar, Kachin (MWM/ZSM); 14, A. midzhan, paratype female, NE Myanmar, Kachin (MWM/ZSM). Scale=1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3936775" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3936775/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">Figs 11–12</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[957,987,1328,1354]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–22" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1892,1917]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,392,1859]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[149,1438,381,1867]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 19–22. Male genitalia of Ammatho (Ammathella) spp. 19, A. gesar sp. nov., holotype, preparation Huang; 20, A. shingwa sp. nov., holotype, slide ZSM Arct. 2019-806; 21, A. garo, holotype, slide MWM31769; 22, A. midzhan, holotype, slide MWM31683." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3936779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3936779/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">21</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1001,1030,1327,1354]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–27" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[214,1378,189,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[205,1382,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 23–27. Female genitalia of Ammatho spp. 23, A. (S.) inexpecta sp. nov., paratype, slide MWM33611; 24, A. (S.) mesortha, slide ZSM Arct.2020-112; 25, A. (A.) shingwa sp. nov., paratype, slide ZSM Arct. 2019-822; 26, A. (A.) garo, paratype, slide MWM31770; 27, A. (A.) midzhan, paratype, slide MWM31768." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3936781" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3936781/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">26</figureCitation>
) due to the similar aedeagus vesica structure, but clearly differ by its juxta lacking a medial process, larger distal costal process, sharper and narrower distal saccular process, slightly longer cornuti on semi-gobular medial diverticulum and shorter and smaller cornuti on ventral medial diverticulum, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2018" box="[633,715,1436,1462]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garo">
<emphasis box="[633,715,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. garo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the juxta bears a well-developed medial process, the distal costal process is minute, the distal saccular process is broad and blunt apically, the cornuti of gobular medial diverticulum are slightly shorter and the cornuti of ventral medial diverticulum are longer and larger. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2018" box="[1203,1329,1508,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="midzhan">
<emphasis box="[1203,1329,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. midzhan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan, 2020" authorityName="Huang &amp; Volynkin &amp; Wang &amp; Fan" authorityYear="2020" box="[1343,1436,1508,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gesar" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1343,1436,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. gesar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,244,1544,1570]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,244,1544,1570]" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be readily distinguished by its generally larger size, more vivid coloration on forewing upperside, more outwards protruding membranous lobe of valva, sharper distal saccular process, much longer aedeagus and vesica with a semi-globular medial diverticulum covered densely by long spines, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2018" box="[1193,1319,1616,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Ammatho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="midzhan">
<emphasis box="[1193,1319,1616,1642]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="586">A. midzhan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the size is generally smaller, coloration on forewing is duller, the membranous lobe of valva is less protruding, distal saccular process is blunt distally, aedeagus is much shorter and the medial diverticulum of vesica is covered by shorter and smaller cornuti.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
